1Ô∏è‚É£ S3

Amazon S3 is an object storage service used to store and retrieve any amount of data.
It is highly scalable, durable, and accessible from anywhere.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Bucket

A bucket is a container for storing objects in S3.
Each bucket has a unique name and is created in a specific AWS region.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Object

An object is a file stored in S3 along with its metadata.
Each object is identified by a unique key within a bucket.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Storage Classes

S3 provides different storage classes like Standard, IA, Glacier, and Deep Archive.
They help reduce cost based on access frequency.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Durability & Availability

S3 provides 99.999999999% (11 nines) durability.
Data is automatically stored across multiple devices and facilities.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Versioning

Versioning keeps multiple versions of an object in the same bucket.
It helps protect against accidental deletion or overwrite.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Encryption

S3 supports encryption at rest and in transit.
It protects data using AWS-managed or customer-managed keys.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Access Control

Access to S3 is controlled using IAM policies, bucket policies, and ACLs.
This ensures only authorized users can access data.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Lifecycle Policy

Lifecycle policies automate moving or deleting objects.
They are used to transition data to cheaper storage classes.

üîü Use Cases

S3 is used for backup, file storage, static website hosting, and log storage.
It is commonly used in data lakes and application storage.
